<%= content_for :heading do %>
  <h1>Typography</h1>
  <p>Sage provides a constrained, purposeful set of typographic styles. These styles map as much as possible to functional roles so you know when each can be used.</p>
<% end %>
<%= content_for :quick_links do %>
  <div class="quick-links">
    <h2 class="quick-links__title t-sage-heading-6">Contents</h2>
    <ul class="quick-links__body t-sage-body-small">
      <li class="quick-links__item">
        <a href="#guidance" class="quick-links__link">Guidance</a>
      </li>
      <li class="quick-links__item">
        <a href="#spec-table" class="quick-links__link">Type Spec Reference</a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
<% end %>
<hr />

<div class="sage-type">
  <p>
    The Sage type system uses a major second modular scale (factor of 1.125) with a base font size of 16px.
  </p>
  <p>
    Typography in our system uses <code>t-sage-</code> classes in order to apply a given typographical specification to an element
    These can be used on any element to apply the desired typographical styles regardless of the tag. This allows a
    wide range of flexibility for applying a desired style to an element while still using the most semantic element possible
    for a given context.
  </p>
  <p>
    Setting styles individual styles manually should be avoided, but where needed, should be sure to use the appropriate
    <%= link_to "design tokens", pages_token_url %>.
    In the end, we prefer adding new entries to the type spec over including one-off styling.
  </p>
  <h2 id="spec-table">Type Spec Reference</h2>
  <table class="sage-specs">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Style</th>
        <th>Class</th>
        <th>Weight</th>
        <th>Size</th>
        <th>Line-height</th>
        <th>Kerning</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-heading-1">Heading 1</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-heading-1</code>
        <td>700</td>
        <td>28.83px</td>
        <td>1.25</td>
        <td>0.3px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-heading-2">Heading 2</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-heading-2</code>
        <td>700</td>
        <td>25.63px</td>
        <td>1.25</td>
        <td>0.3px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-heading-3">Heading 3</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-heading-3</code>
        <td>700</td>
        <td>22.78px</td>
        <td>1.25</td>
        <td>0.3px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-heading-4">Heading 4</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-heading-4</code>
        <td>600</td>
        <td>20.25px</td>
        <td>1.25</td>
        <td>0.3px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-heading-5">Heading 5</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-heading-5</code>
        <td>600</td>
        <td>18px</td>
        <td>1.25</td>
        <td>0.3px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-heading-6">Heading 6</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-heading-6</code>
        <td>600</td>
        <td>16px</td>
        <td>1.25</td>
        <td>0.3px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-body">Body*</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-body</code>
        <td>400*</td>
        <td>16px</td>
        <td>1.75</td>
        <td>0.2px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-body-small">Small Body*</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-body-small</code>
        <td>400*</td>
        <td>14.22px</td>
        <td>1.75</td>
        <td>0.2px</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="t-sage-body-xsmall">Extra Small Body*</span></td>
        <td><code>t-sage-body-xsmall</code>
        <td>400*</td>
        <td>12.64px</td>
        <td>1.75</td>
        <td>0.2px</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
    <tfoot>
      <tr>
        <td colspan="6">
          <p class="t-sage-body-xsmall">
            * The <code>t-sage-body{-size}</code> classes also have weight variations:
               append <code>-med</code> for <span class="t-sage-body-xsmall-med">medium (500)</span>;
               append <code>-semi</code> for <span class="t-sage-body-xsmall-semi">semibold (600)</span>;
               append <code>-bold</code> for <span class="t-sage-body-xsmall-bold">bold (700)</span>
           </p>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tfoot>
  </table>

  <p>
    The type specs above map logically to corresponding HTML elements, as well as the following:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <span class="t-sage-body">Body</span> is used as the default type style, and is thus applied to elements such as
      <code>li</code>, <code>dd</code>, <code>td</code>, <code>blockquote</code>, and more.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Body Bold</strong> is used for elements that are typically bolded such as
      <code>tr</code>, <code>dt</code>, <code>strong</code>, and <code>b</code>.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    As an example, see here how the "Heading 3" type spec can be applied to an
    <code>h3</code> element:
  </p>
</div>

<div class="docs-container">
  <h3 class="t-sage-heading-3">Lorem ipsum dolor sit</h3>
  <div class="sage-code-snippet">
    <pre class="prettyprint"><code>&lt;h3 class="t-sage-heading-3"&gt;Lorem ipsum dolor sit&lt;/h3&gt;</code></pre>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sage-type">
  <p>
    But the exact specs can also be applied to any element such as a <code>span</code>.
    This is not meant to be an excuse for using non-semantic markup, but rather,
    to free a spec to be applied to the most semantic element in context regardless
    of the spec's name.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="docs-container">
  <span class="t-sage-heading-3">Lorem ipsum dolor sit</span>
  <div class="sage-code-snippet">
    <pre class="prettyprint"><code>&lt;span class="t-sage-heading-3"&gt;Lorem ipsum dolor sit&lt;/span&gt;</code></pre>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sage-type">
  <p>
    For setting text in open areas where simpler markup is desired, or where a
    content management system controls the markup being output, we recommend applying
    the <code>sage-type</code> class on a container around such content. This
    leads to some default styling applied to the tags within the container
    include our preferred colors and block spacing.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="docs-container">
  <div class="sage-type">
    <h3>User-generated content</h3>
    <p>See how content inside this <code>sage-type</code> container automatically recieves corresponding type specs?</p>
  </div>
